Most senders think summer isn't a good time to focus on cold emails.

But smart teams know this is exactly when you should lean in.

Because while everyone else is waiting, you have the chance to stand out. Here's how you should act now to prepare for a strong September and October.

Read the blog post ( https://hunter.io/blog/does-b2b-slow-down-in-summer/?utm_campaign=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_content=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io ) 
Cold emails don’t get ignored because they’re cold. According to 71% of decision makers ( https://hunter.io/blog/making-your-cold-emails-relevant-101/?utm_campaign=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_content=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io#:~:text=71%25%20of%20the%20surveyed%20decision%20makers%20said%20they%20typically%20don%E2%80%99t%20reply%20to%20cold%20emails%20because%20they%20don%E2%80%99t%20address%20relevant%20problems.%20We%20also%20found%20that%20personalizing%20your%20emails%2C%20which%20helps%20make%20them%20relevant%2C%20can%20greatly%20boost%20reply%20rates. ), they’re ignoring you because your email is irrelevant. 

Relevance comes from targeting the right people with the right offer. This blog suggests a workflow to adapt your messaging when you have multiple contacts at a single company.

Read the blog post ( https://hunter.io/blog/how-to-use-ai-in-your-emails-without-losing-your-voice/?utm_campaign=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_content=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io ) What if you could get feedback from your leads before it leaves your inbox?

With this blog, you can use AI to predict and analyze cold email performance—before you hit Send.

Read the blog post ( https://hunter.io/blog/can-ai-predict-if-your-cold-email-will-work-yes-heres-the-exact-prompt/?utm_campaign=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_content=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io )

Most senders think summer isn't a good time to focus on cold emails.

But smart teams know this is exactly when you should lean in.

Because while everyone else is waiting, you have the chance to stand out. Here's how you should act now to prepare for a strong September and October.

Read the blog post ( https://hunter.io/blog/does-b2b-slow-down-in-summer/?utm_campaign=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_content=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io ) 
Cold emails don’t get ignored because they’re cold. According to 71% of decision makers ( https://hunter.io/blog/making-your-cold-emails-relevant-101/?utm_campaign=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_content=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io#:~:text=71%25%20of%20the%20surveyed%20decision%20makers%20said%20they%20typically%20don%E2%80%99t%20reply%20to%20cold%20emails%20because%20they%20don%E2%80%99t%20address%20relevant%20problems.%20We%20also%20found%20that%20personalizing%20your%20emails%2C%20which%20helps%20make%20them%20relevant%2C%20can%20greatly%20boost%20reply%20rates. ), they’re ignoring you because your email is irrelevant. 

Relevance comes from targeting the right people with the right offer. This blog suggests a workflow to adapt your messaging when you have multiple contacts at a single company.

Read the blog post ( https://hunter.io/blog/how-to-use-ai-in-your-emails-without-losing-your-voice/?utm_campaign=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_content=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io ) What if you could get feedback from your leads before it leaves your inbox?

With this blog, you can use AI to predict and analyze cold email performance—before you hit Send.

Read the blog post ( https://hunter.io/blog/can-ai-predict-if-your-cold-email-will-work-yes-heres-the-exact-prompt/?utm_campaign=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_content=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io )

Contact us ( https://hunter.io/contact?utm_campaign=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_content=2025-07+Content+Newsletter&utm_medium=email_action&utm_source=customer.io ).

Designer </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/6214d137-6980-4ef7-adf5-6058a97848cd?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">Daniella Kallmeyer</a><span> has been dressing New York Liberty’s head coach </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/c26dc65c-19ec-4fc5-921d-929dc14596a5?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">Sandy Brondello</a><span> for the past few seasons so the trip felt like a natural extension for the fashion brand. This came on the heels of luxury sock company </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/4e9ee8f6-c323-4489-af4c-c81cca0e6f4d?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">Comme Si</a><span> hosting a crew in the Austrian Alps, </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/21dc5770-80e4-40d0-9d41-22e8e4ea33f8?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">Matteau</a><span> traveling to Côte d'Azur with friends, and </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/b884faa8-4248-43c9-8077-1baf2a4929df?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">DÔEN</a><span> bringing Substackers to Nantucket.</span></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">For a long time, the brand trip felt like an activation reserved for the Tartes and Poppis of the world. DÔEN</figcaption></figure></div><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>As the types of brands that pull this marketing lever expand, so do the teams that plan them. </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/13c8028c-447f-4cf9-8807-8dd1387708b4?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">Care of Chan</a><span>, the agency behind </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/37f919bf-546a-419e-9f69-679eac5379df?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">J.Crew’s recent Puglia trip</a><span>, originally started as a PR and talent management agency. A few years ago, they pivoted their focus to events—which now also includes brand trips. </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/5b440b1f-5230-461d-ae61-66090020e6ae?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">Studio BOUM</a><span> is the design and production agency behind the </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/2d704d0f-3b12-417f-9a56-d179cfc8a8fd?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">Rhode Summer Club</a><span> in Mallorca. A </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/97f3b52f-d0fd-4826-9742-04932095f9fd?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">headline</a><span> just last year described the agency as being behind “fashion’s most memorable runway shows”. Their services are growing. </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/770379bf-e8fd-401e-a817-e9264c7d31a5?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">STUDIO SANTOS</a><span>, started by two former employees of luxury travel brand Prior, have broken off to start their own company that will “distill your brand into experiences grounded in the idea of place”.</span></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>When I asked </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/2181c550-0136-49d7-9e12-3307a5689c0a?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">Sue Chan</a><span>, founder of Care of Chan, if brand trip requests have increased, she told me, “Yes, inquiries have increased—not just for influencer trips, but for in-person events overall.” She goes on to say, “In an increasingly remote world, shared, real-life experiences hold lasting magic. In this digital era, I believe the most effective path forward is rooted in grassroots marketing and immersive, in-person events.”</span></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>These brand trips aren’t just for the people invited though—they are for the hundreds of thousands of people who follow the guests too. Two weeks ago I had never heard of the brand “</span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/3816174d-9831-4326-9de6-155c2188f43f?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">Hotel Lobby Candle</a><span>”, but thanks to a recent trip to Montauk with influencers like </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/ca1b45b5-1014-456d-9f02-126a34c39876?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">Hannah Chody</a><span> and </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/3949d78a-2632-4599-bbb0-f4b78b7deb19?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">Barbarah William</a><span>, I now know that they have a tomato-scented candle. </span></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>I reached out to Hotel Lobby Candle founder </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/c8f8eeef-58c9-47d8-b1b7-9deebc41b1b3?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">Lindsay Silberman</a><span> to understand if the trip had an impact on sales. She shared that the brand saw a 50% increase in all sales compared to an average week YTD and that sales of the seasonal candle the trip was themed around (the Hamptons candle) saw a 419% increase in sales vs. this week last year.</span></p><div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px;line-height: 26px;margin: 32px auto;"><figure style="width: 100%;margin: 0 auto;"><table Chan said, “Guest dynamics can make or break the experience. Avoid cliques by inviting people who don’t know each other yet but should. And always include a few big personalities to keep the energy high and conversation flowing.” Brands like </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/afccbf16-169b-4724-80fb-b8200784ff6d?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">Topicals</a><span> have done such an impressive job at selecting influencers for their trips that they’ve inspired people to </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/55d694f4-8615-46f8-9d3d-898baf857da3?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">make viral TikToks</a><span> praising them. ROI can be top of mind too. One marketer who has planned brand trips told me that they will select people who already do well through affiliate because they know they will post their links without being asked.</span></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>Then there’s the cost. I spoke with a handful of marketers who are familiar with the economics of brand trips to find out just how much is being spent. I learned that trips can range from $100K all of the way up to $700K. Obviously a lot of this is dependent on the location, length, and the size of the trip. Another factor is if the hotel is discounting rooms or if other brands are paying to have </span><em>their</em><span> products also be included.</span></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Sue from Care of Chan shared, “Like anything in life, there’s a Mini Cooper version and a Rolls-Royce version. If you're working with a limited budget, focus on one standout moment. Or keep it local. With the right guests, you can still make a lasting impact. But success isn’t about how much you spend—it’s about how purposeful you make it.”</p><div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px;line-height: 26px;margin: 32px auto;"><figure text:
View this post on the web at https://www.milkkarten.net/p/the-business-of-brand-trips

Two weeks ago I watched as some of my favorite follows attended the WNBA All-Star Game with Nike and Kallmeyer [ https://substack.com/redirect/78355325-5f96-404d-acd7-9895ad5bb041?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]. Designer Daniella Kallmeyer [ https://substack.com/redirect/6214d137-6980-4ef7-adf5-6058a97848cd?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] has been dressing New York Liberty’s head coach Sandy Brondello [ https://substack.com/redirect/c26dc65c-19ec-4fc5-921d-929dc14596a5?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] for the past few seasons so the trip felt like a natural extension for the fashion brand. This came on the heels of luxury sock company Comme Si [ https://substack.com/redirect/4e9ee8f6-c323-4489-af4c-c81cca0e6f4d?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] hosting a crew in the Austrian Alps, Matteau [ https://substack.com/redirect/21dc5770-80e4-40d0-9d41-22e8e4ea33f8?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] traveling to Côte d'Azur with friends, and DÔEN [ https://substack.com/redirect/b884faa8-4248-43c9-8077-1baf2a4929df?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] bringing Substackers to Nantucket.
For a long time, the brand trip felt like an activation reserved for the Tartes and Poppis of the world. That’s changing.
As the types of brands that pull this marketing lever expand, so do the teams that plan them. Care of Chan [ https://substack.com/redirect/13c8028c-447f-4cf9-8807-8dd1387708b4?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], the agency behind J.Crew’s recent Puglia trip [ https://substack.com/redirect/37f919bf-546a-419e-9f69-679eac5379df?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], originally started as a PR and talent management agency. A few years ago, they pivoted their focus to events—which now also includes brand trips. Studio BOUM [ https://substack.com/redirect/5b440b1f-5230-461d-ae61-66090020e6ae?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] is the design and production agency behind the Rhode Summer Club [ https://substack.com/redirect/2d704d0f-3b12-417f-9a56-d179cfc8a8fd?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] in Mallorca. A headline [ https://substack.com/redirect/97f3b52f-d0fd-4826-9742-04932095f9fd?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] just last year described the agency as being behind “fashion’s most memorable runway shows”. Their services are growing. STUDIO SANTOS [ https://substack.com/redirect/770379bf-e8fd-401e-a817-e9264c7d31a5?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], started by two former employees of luxury travel brand Prior, have broken off to start their own company that will “distill your brand into experiences grounded in the idea of place”.
When I asked Sue Chan [ https://substack.com/redirect/2181c550-0136-49d7-9e12-3307a5689c0a?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], founder of Care of Chan, if brand trip requests have increased, she told me, “Yes, inquiries have increased—not just for influencer trips, but for in-person events overall.” She goes on to say, “In an increasingly remote world, shared, real-life experiences hold lasting magic. In this digital era, I believe the most effective path forward is rooted in grassroots marketing and immersive, in-person events.”
These brand trips aren’t just for the people invited though—they are for the hundreds of thousands of people who follow the guests too. Two weeks ago I had never heard of the brand “Hotel Lobby Candle [ https://substack.com/redirect/3816174d-9831-4326-9de6-155c2188f43f?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]”, but thanks to a recent trip to Montauk with influencers like Hannah Chody [ https://substack.com/redirect/ca1b45b5-1014-456d-9f02-126a34c39876?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] and Barbarah William [ https://substack.com/redirect/3949d78a-2632-4599-bbb0-f4b78b7deb19?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], I now know that they have a tomato-scented candle. 
I reached out to Hotel Lobby Candle founder Lindsay Silberman [ https://substack.com/redirect/c8f8eeef-58c9-47d8-b1b7-9deebc41b1b3?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] to understand if the trip had an impact on sales. She shared that the brand saw a 50% increase in all sales compared to an average week YTD and that sales of the seasonal candle the trip was themed around (the Hamptons candle) saw a 419% increase in sales vs. this week last year.
When it comes to curating who gets to attend these trips, Sue from Care of Chan said, “Guest dynamics can make or break the experience. Avoid cliques by inviting people who don’t know each other yet but should. And always include a few big personalities to keep the energy high and conversation flowing.” Brands like Topicals [ https://substack.com/redirect/afccbf16-169b-4724-80fb-b8200784ff6d?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] have done such an impressive job at selecting influencers for their trips that they’ve inspired people to make viral TikToks [ https://substack.com/redirect/55d694f4-8615-46f8-9d3d-898baf857da3?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] praising them. ROI can be top of mind too. One marketer who has planned brand trips told me that they will select people who already do well through affiliate because they know they will post their links without being asked.
Then there’s the cost. I spoke with a handful of marketers who are familiar with the economics of brand trips to find out just how much is being spent. I learned that trips can range from $100K all of the way up to $700K. Obviously a lot of this is dependent on the location, length, and the size of the trip. Another factor is if the hotel is discounting rooms or if other brands are paying to have their products also be included.
Sue from Care of Chan shared, “Like anything in life, there’s a Mini Cooper version and a Rolls-Royce version. If you're working with a limited budget, focus on one standout moment. Or keep it local. With the right guests, you can still make a lasting impact. But success isn’t about how much you spend—it’s about how purposeful you make it.”
And what about the influencer fees? From conversations that I’ve had with both marketers and influencers, it seems like the majority of brands do not pay influencers to attend or post. It’s sort of an “unspoken contract”—because the brand is covering all other costs, it’s assumed the influencer will document the trip. 
One influencer I spoke with said that they avoid attending trips that don’t pay them to post. They said that their fee for a video or post far exceeds what the brand is likely paying for them to be there. This can be true. A marketer I talked to shared that the amount of posts the influencers share often exceeds what the brand could afford with standard sponsored rates. Still, some brands make trips so desirable that an influencer will pitch themselves to get an invite, like creator Serena Kerrigan did in this post [ https://substack.com/redirect/90524acc-f10e-492e-9125-4e496b1bbff8?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] about the Rhode trip.
Finally, as consumers see more brand trips pop up across their feeds—usually mixed in between current events and breaking news—it’s important that they understand the why behind the trip.
Earlier this year, hydration company Waterboy received criticism [ https://substack.com/redirect/78c91822-d073-4022-83c8-e554a1066351?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] that their trip to Tulum had zero connection to their product. This TikTok [ https://substack.com/redirect/5fe68e23-39b5-4e6f-93e5-adfd8f20b67c?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] breaking down why the trip didn’t resonate has 2.4M views. One comment reads, “No like wtf is going on with the videos of all of them looking extremely hungover and tired yet the brand is known for reviving you.”
In contrast, when Kerrygold [ https://substack.com/redirect/58bfcd6e-fa00-4f73-a2a9-e7d96e36b3d8?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] brought influencers to Ireland on a “butter brand trip” to see how their product is made, audiences reacted positively. Among the guests was Katie [ https://substack.com/@sundaystack?utm_source=about-page ]  [ https://substack.com/@sundaystack?utm_source=about-page ]Zukhovich [ https://substack.com/@sundaystack?utm_source=about-page ], creator at @babytamagooo [ https://substack.com/redirect/f5f9e639-ad28-4b2e-8919-5ec95b62b938?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] and writer of the sunday stack [ https://open.substack.com/pub/sundaystack ]. Her video documenting the experience [ https://substack.com/redirect/c74417ad-3be2-4c2c-b515-2f5ccd61b1d8?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] has over 1M views across platforms and spurred other [ https://substack.com/redirect/ff887936-be67-4528-8fb8-de31a7517708?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] viral posts from creators [ https://substack.com/redirect/ff887936-be67-4528-8fb8-de31a7517708?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] hoping to get noticed by Kerrygold.
When I asked Katie why the trip was received so well by her audience, she told me, “I think the typical brand trips can often feel kind of disconnected from the product. They’re definitely lavish and beautiful but it’s rare to see the actual home of a brand, see how it’s made, packed, etc. Everything was just integrated so naturally, it wasn’t so in your face like some can be.”
As more brands inevitably plan their own trips, it’ll be imperative that they make the purpose of the trip clear to consumers. The line between “this is out of touch” and “invite me next time” is thin.
If you enjoy free essays like this one, you can upgrade to a paid Link in Bio subscription [ https://substack.com/redirect/26cdcdad-5dc2-49e8-8e12-e0f8da729ee1?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]. You’ll get access to the very active and very helpful Discord.
It’s likely an educational expense at your company—here’s a template [ https://substack.com/redirect/3722000c-87cf-439b-b7b5-7816431ac131?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] for you to use when asking your manager.
Finally, I’ll be donating a portion of this month’s subscriber revenue to World Central Kitchen [ https://substack.com/redirect/a7bb5a13-74ed-4c52-81a8-4f7fd9b4cca1?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]. textAsHtml:
View this post on the web at https://www.milkkarten.net/p/the-business-of-brand-trips

Two weeks ago I watched as some of my favorite follows attended the WNBA All-Star Game with Nike and Kallmeyer [ https://substack.com/redirect/78355325-5f96-404d-acd7-9895ad5bb041?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]. Designer Daniella Kallmeyer [ https://substack.com/redirect/6214d137-6980-4ef7-adf5-6058a97848cd?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] has been dressing New York Liberty’s head coach Sandy Brondello [ https://substack.com/redirect/c26dc65c-19ec-4fc5-921d-929dc14596a5?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] for the past few seasons so the trip felt like a natural extension for the fashion brand. This came on the heels of luxury sock company Comme Si [ https://substack.com/redirect/4e9ee8f6-c323-4489-af4c-c81cca0e6f4d?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] hosting a crew in the Austrian Alps, Matteau [ https://substack.com/redirect/21dc5770-80e4-40d0-9d41-22e8e4ea33f8?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] traveling to Côte d'Azur with friends, and DÔEN [ https://substack.com/redirect/b884faa8-4248-43c9-8077-1baf2a4929df?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] bringing Substackers to Nantucket.
For a long time, the brand trip felt like an activation reserved for the Tartes and Poppis of the world. That’s changing.
As the types of brands that pull this marketing lever expand, so do the teams that plan them. Care of Chan [ https://substack.com/redirect/13c8028c-447f-4cf9-8807-8dd1387708b4?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], the agency behind J.Crew’s recent Puglia trip [ https://substack.com/redirect/37f919bf-546a-419e-9f69-679eac5379df?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], originally started as a PR and talent management agency. A few years ago, they pivoted their focus to events—which now also includes brand trips. Studio BOUM [ https://substack.com/redirect/5b440b1f-5230-461d-ae61-66090020e6ae?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] is the design and production agency behind the Rhode Summer Club [ https://substack.com/redirect/2d704d0f-3b12-417f-9a56-d179cfc8a8fd?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] in Mallorca. A headline [ https://substack.com/redirect/97f3b52f-d0fd-4826-9742-04932095f9fd?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] just last year described the agency as being behind “fashion’s most memorable runway shows”. Their services are growing. STUDIO SANTOS [ https://substack.com/redirect/770379bf-e8fd-401e-a817-e9264c7d31a5?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], started by two former employees of luxury travel brand Prior, have broken off to start their own company that will “distill your brand into experiences grounded in the idea of place”.
When I asked Sue Chan [ https://substack.com/redirect/2181c550-0136-49d7-9e12-3307a5689c0a?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], founder of Care of Chan, if brand trip requests have increased, she told me, “Yes, inquiries have increased—not just for influencer trips, but for in-person events overall.” She goes on to say, “In an increasingly remote world, shared, real-life experiences hold lasting magic. In this digital era, I believe the most effective path forward is rooted in grassroots marketing and immersive, in-person events.”
These brand trips aren’t just for the people invited though—they are for the hundreds of thousands of people who follow the guests too. Two weeks ago I had never heard of the brand “Hotel Lobby Candle [ https://substack.com/redirect/3816174d-9831-4326-9de6-155c2188f43f?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]”, but thanks to a recent trip to Montauk with influencers like Hannah Chody [ https://substack.com/redirect/ca1b45b5-1014-456d-9f02-126a34c39876?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] and Barbarah William [ https://substack.com/redirect/3949d78a-2632-4599-bbb0-f4b78b7deb19?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], I now know that they have a tomato-scented candle.
I reached out to Hotel Lobby Candle founder Lindsay Silberman [ https://substack.com/redirect/c8f8eeef-58c9-47d8-b1b7-9deebc41b1b3?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] to understand if the trip had an impact on sales. She shared that the brand saw a 50% increase in all sales compared to an average week YTD and that sales of the seasonal candle the trip was themed around (the Hamptons candle) saw a 419% increase in sales vs. this week last year.
When it comes to curating who gets to attend these trips, Sue from Care of Chan said, “Guest dynamics can make or break the experience. Avoid cliques by inviting people who don’t know each other yet but should. And always include a few big personalities to keep the energy high and conversation flowing.” Brands like Topicals [ https://substack.com/redirect/afccbf16-169b-4724-80fb-b8200784ff6d?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] have done such an impressive job at selecting influencers for their trips that they’ve inspired people to make viral TikToks [ https://substack.com/redirect/55d694f4-8615-46f8-9d3d-898baf857da3?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] praising them. ROI can be top of mind too. One marketer who has planned brand trips told me that they will select people who already do well through affiliate because they know they will post their links without being asked.
Then there’s the cost. I spoke with a handful of marketers who are familiar with the economics of brand trips to find out just how much is being spent. I learned that trips can range from $100K all of the way up to $700K. Obviously a lot of this is dependent on the location, length, and the size of the trip. Another factor is if the hotel is discounting rooms or if other brands are paying to have their products also be included.
Sue from Care of Chan shared, “Like anything in life, there’s a Mini Cooper version and a Rolls-Royce version. If you're working with a limited budget, focus on one standout moment. Or keep it local. With the right guests, you can still make a lasting impact. But success isn’t about how much you spend—it’s about how purposeful you make it.”
And what about the influencer fees? From conversations that I’ve had with both marketers and influencers, it seems like the majority of brands do not pay influencers to attend or post. It’s sort of an “unspoken contract”—because the brand is covering all other costs, it’s assumed the influencer will document the trip.
One influencer I spoke with said that they avoid attending trips that don’t pay them to post. They said that their fee for a video or post far exceeds what the brand is likely paying for them to be there. This can be true. A marketer I talked to shared that the amount of posts the influencers share often exceeds what the brand could afford with standard sponsored rates. Still, some brands make trips so desirable that an influencer will pitch themselves to get an invite, like creator Serena Kerrigan did in this post [ https://substack.com/redirect/90524acc-f10e-492e-9125-4e496b1bbff8?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] about the Rhode trip.
Finally, as consumers see more brand trips pop up across their feeds—usually mixed in between current events and breaking news—it’s important that they understand the why behind the trip.
Earlier this year, hydration company Waterboy received criticism [ https://substack.com/redirect/78c91822-d073-4022-83c8-e554a1066351?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] that their trip to Tulum had zero connection to their product. This TikTok [ https://substack.com/redirect/5fe68e23-39b5-4e6f-93e5-adfd8f20b67c?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] breaking down why the trip didn’t resonate has 2.4M views. One comment reads, “No like wtf is going on with the videos of all of them looking extremely hungover and tired yet the brand is known for reviving you.”
In contrast, when Kerrygold [ https://substack.com/redirect/58bfcd6e-fa00-4f73-a2a9-e7d96e36b3d8?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] brought influencers to Ireland on a “butter brand trip” to see how their product is made, audiences reacted positively. Among the guests was Katie [ https://substack.com/@sundaystack?utm_source=about-page ] [ https://substack.com/@sundaystack?utm_source=about-page ]Zukhovich [ https://substack.com/@sundaystack?utm_source=about-page ], creator at @babytamagooo [ https://substack.com/redirect/f5f9e639-ad28-4b2e-8919-5ec95b62b938?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] and writer of the sunday stack [ https://open.substack.com/pub/sundaystack ]. Her video documenting the experience [ https://substack.com/redirect/c74417ad-3be2-4c2c-b515-2f5ccd61b1d8?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] has over 1M views across platforms and spurred other [ https://substack.com/redirect/ff887936-be67-4528-8fb8-de31a7517708?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] viral posts from creators [ https://substack.com/redirect/ff887936-be67-4528-8fb8-de31a7517708?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] hoping to get noticed by Kerrygold.
When I asked Katie why the trip was received so well by her audience, she told me, “I think the typical brand trips can often feel kind of disconnected from the product. They’re definitely lavish and beautiful but it’s rare to see the actual home of a brand, see how it’s made, packed, etc. Everything was just integrated so naturally, it wasn’t so in your face like some can be.”
As more brands inevitably plan their own trips, it’ll be imperative that they make the purpose of the trip clear to consumers. The line between “this is out of touch” and “invite me next time” is thin.
If you enjoy free essays like this one, you can upgrade to a paid Link in Bio subscription [ https://substack.com/redirect/26cdcdad-5dc2-49e8-8e12-e0f8da729ee1?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]. You’ll get access to the very active and very helpful Discord.
It’s likely an educational expense at your company—here’s a template [ https://substack.com/redirect/3722000c-87cf-439b-b7b5-7816431ac131?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] for you to use when asking your manager.
Finally, I’ll be donating a portion of this month’s subscriber revenue to World Central Kitchen [ https://substack.com/redirect/a7bb5a13-74ed-4c52-81a8-4f7fd9b4cca1?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]. If you want to learn more about their important work, I recommend reading this op-ed [ https://substack.com/redirect/0e9665c7-2252-41c5-969a-d81973f4ba3a?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] from founder José Andrés.

Unsubscribe https://substack.com/redirect/2/eyJlIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubWlsa2thcnRlbi5uZXQvYWN0aW9uL2Rpc2FibGVfZW1haWw_.gCw1DiENT1nY3fWmzLdHE4ufjhPjjZNIhOnronkdJos?

Welcome to July’s ICYMI: You Need to Know It Edition, recapping the major updates you might have missed this month. Astronomer partnered [ https://substack.com/redirect/c2e83831-8c64-4262-a045-517ee4b752c7?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] with Maximum Effort and Gwyneth Paltrow to change the narrative; American Eagle disappointed while [ https://substack.com/redirect/23eaf65d-6b16-4a7d-8923-fcd1a757b985?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] Ralph Lauren excelled [ https://substack.com/redirect/23eaf65d-6b16-4a7d-8923-fcd1a757b985?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]; and employees on social are an asset [ https://substack.com/redirect/7338dad0-e04f-4fdc-9aa0-66d921b2e6b1?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] but then Aeropostale [ https://substack.com/redirect/8697c6fd-58f1-4bb6-a93f-fe11a2f9111b?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], Hollister [ https://substack.com/redirect/32d0f696-641c-4ebe-83ee-cacab7cc125d?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] and even JC Penney [ https://substack.com/redirect/b1fe2381-33c2-4626-a3ef-6a234dd647d9?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] could have told you that this summer. Now, let’s get to the good stuff!
📋 THE THINGS YOU NEED TO KNOW
8 key platform updates we saw in July and why they matter
3 places your audience is hanging out beyond the Feed
Where Carousels fit in your content mix
Making the most of Instagram Reels
The lifecyle of a TikTok post versus an Instagram post

html:
We are holding our next Tender Writing Introduction webinar on Wednesday 10th September 2025.

This live and interactive webinar is an excellent introduction into the bidding process and tendering within the public sector.

On the day we will cover:
• Understanding Procurement Jargon
• Where to find suitable tenders
• What realistically should I bid for – Making the right ‘Bid/No Bid’ decisions
• What does my business need to prove/demonstrate to be seen as a credible supplier by the public sector
• Choosing the right references and then writing descriptively to fully show your experience/credibility
• Basic Do’s and Don’ts of Bid / Tender writing – Important advice

Who should attend?
• Anyone currently involved, or looking to start Tendering for Public Sector contracts
• Any organisation who wants to win ‘Public Sector’ contracts or contracts through the formal procurement process
• Businesses who want to get on the route to ‘contract readiness’

Why should you attend?
This workshop is designed to provide delegates with an understanding of the process, why it is being used and most importantly how to be successful

Benefits from attending:
• Increasing your knowledge of the procurement process
• To further understand the public procurement process
• Increase chances of success
• To develop efficient and effective bidding systems

Our Trainer:
An active Bid Manager who really understands the bidding environment and how it applies in practice; not just the theory. A vast amount of experience and expertise supporting a range of blue chip, SME and third sector clients with their bids.

Feedback from people who recently attended our training webinar:
"Superb training session learnt a lot of new ideas and this will help in securing future tenders"
"The course was very informative, and all areas were covered"
"It was a Step by step guide with good course content and I learned things I didn't know which will definitely help in the future"
"The trainer is very engaging - Refreshing to have an authentic facilitator on a topic like this"
"A great training day. I can't imagine there are many people with more experience in tender writing"
"A must for anyone considering completing a Tender"

Pricing for this webinar is as follows:
If you are a current paid subscriber of B2B Quote Tenders the cost is £139.00 plus VAT per person.
If you have a free registration with B2B Quote Tenders the cost is £159.00 plus VAT per person.

To ensure you get the most from this webinar we are limiting the number of places available.
The webinar will take place between 9:00am - 1:00pm on Wednesday 10th September 2025.

If you are interested in attending please complete your booking within the Tender Training page when logged into your account with B2B Quote.

Alternatively you can register your booking by email to: onlinetraining@b2bquotetenders.co.uk

The cut off date for booking places is: Friday 29th August 2025. Payment is required in full to secure your place.

If you do have any questions please do not hesitate to contact us.

Best regards

James Rowley

html:
How to Screen Record and Publish Videos Using Only Your Gmail Account

Hi there,

Let's say you want to screen record a video.

What tools do you need? What software will you have to buy, install, and learn?

Answer: Gmail.

You read that right.

With Free Screencast Recording for Gmail, you can create your own screencast.

But what this blog shows you, is how you can download your screencast videos so that you can:

  1. Save them in a folder,
  2. Embed them in a blog platform like Wordpress, or
  3. Upload them directly to video sites like Youtube.

This week's 5-minute blog post shows you how.

It includes a screencast video we made using the exact steps we detail in the article...
How to Create a Screencast Video

bit about the content pillars the team set up for Arthur on TikTok—it’s a really clever framework. Can you share a bit more about those?</strong></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong>CC: </strong><span>The TikTok was first launched in 2022—before I joined GBH—as a team effort that consisted of the digital and marketing/communications teams at GBH and a Gen Z consulting firm. The launch’s goal was to lean into the fun of TikTok while also highlighting why Arthur is such an iconic brand in the children's media space. The content pillars created were:</span></p><ul style="margin-top: 0;padding: 0;"><li style="margin: 8px 0 0 32px;mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style="color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: border-box;padding-left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;">“Girls That Get It Get It”: lean into the humor to remind audiences that Arthur is relatable and entertaining at any age.</p></li><li style="margin: 8px 0 0 32px;mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style="color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: border-box;padding-left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;">“Not Me Crying Right Now”: celebrate iconic Arthur moments and the nostalgia.</p></li><li style="margin: 8px 0 0 32px;mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style="color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: border-box;padding-left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;">“Read All About It”: Arthur was originally created to teach kids about reading but became a show about the joys of growing up so we choose clips that highlight the important lessons Arthur and his friends shared over the years.</p></li></ul><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">As our account and audience have evolved, we don’t hold as strict to these original pillars, but they do still influence the base of our strategy. We want our accounts to exist as entertainment, an extension of Arthur content. This requires being mindful of how much promotion we do and never forgetting the core connections our audience has with the Elwood City squad. Foundational pillars have been a great way to do that.</p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong><span>RK: I love the idea of building content around how you want the audience to react. So smart. I think some children's shows and movies are reluctant to lean into their lore—it's been fun to see</span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/cef287ab-023d-422d-ba54-afe351340cb5?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;"> Shrek</a><span> finally embrace it, for example. How does Arthur lore and nostalgia play into your strategy?</span></strong></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong>CC: </strong><span>It’s at the core of it! Given our enormous catalog of show content, tapping into fan nostalgia and building community through our archives has been such a game-changer for us across so many GBH-affiliated accounts. A great example of how we utilize this is comment replies. Arthur fans often comment their favorite quotes, songs, or scenes on our posts, starting threads filled with nostalgia and wholesome memories. It’s incredibly heartwarming. We love to track down those clips and </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/86af38ff-bd17-4c82-ab02-33525e6c9684?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">post them as comment replies</a><span>, when we can. It encourages future engagement and introduces fan-favorite scenes to more viewers, but more importantly, it serves an audience that’s supported us since the beginning.</span></p><div an encyclopedic knowledge of clips and scenes from Arthur?</strong></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong>CC: </strong><span>I grew up watching Arthur myself and I am certainly more familiar than most, but unfortunately I do not have encyclopedic knowledge. 25 seasons is a lot to memorize! GBH has years of internal documentation I fall back on. I also collaborate closely with the Arthur producers, our communications/marketing team, and our digital team who all contribute their own expertise. There is also an incredibly detailed </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/3c2ea6f9-ef11-47b2-a7bd-481c3880790b?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">fan-run Arthur wiki</a><span> that rivals our own in-house knowledge!</span></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong>RK: I'd love to dig into how you've used the account to message and organize around the funding cuts. What did that strategy initially look like and how has it evolved over the past few months?</strong></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong>CC: </strong><span>This has been a group effort across the entire PBS landscape, rallying around </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/5041df93-3e9b-4e4b-86b1-3ac9b8350776?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">Protect My Public Media</a><span>. For us, Arthur was a key part of this from the beginning. Like I emphasized earlier, we’ve spent years building trust and mutual support with our audience. We hoped this community agreed about the importance of PBS KIDS. Spoiler alert: They blew us away.</span></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>Our strategy was to use recognizable, familiar images and clips from the show with action-packed language to build awareness of the value of our programming and what’s at stake. As </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/766904c5-cfe2-45be-acdd-3309dbfd88d4?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">one of our posts said</a><span>, “We ride at dawn for PBS. Who’s riding with us?” That’s really like a thesis for our entire approach.</span></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Our content matters and connects with people. We trusted in that legacy enough to tap into it. Conveying emotions of frustration, sadness and resiliency through beloved characters like Arthur, D.W., Sue Ellen, and others seems to really resonate with our fans.</p><div #6979d3;text-decoration: none;"> the Arthur fist post</a><span> came together?</span></strong></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong>CC: by </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/622c01f8-e840-49a2-aad2-170068ef025f?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" target="_blank" rel="" style="color: #003569;text-decoration: none;">@arthur.pbs</a></div></div></div><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">If I’m going to ask people to listen to our arguments for why federal funding matters, I have to get them to care. The fist carries immediate recognition, strong emotional resonance, and a form of frankness that can be challenging to nail with a brand social channel. Having never previously wielded the power of the fist from the official Arthur POV also brought a certain level of seriousness. It was the perfect vessel for getting our message out quickly and effectively.</p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>What surprised me was the lasting power of the meme! It’s not only still getting engagement, but I’ve come across reposts organically in comment sections, Reddit threads, and more. GBH has since made it into </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/200f5a2e-9934-491c-a543-23c728f01632?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">shirts</a><span>, </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/a5d2d5f4-0f8c-441a-9e9b-472824941157?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">stickers</a><span>, and even a </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/12e984ac-222c-4e10-a1ec-c544f63bf28a?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">gif</a><span>. It was also featured on our </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/2993d919-1be0-49ba-9f5c-9de365a86351?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">1,350 sq. ft. digital mural</a><span> overlooking the Mass Pike. It clearly captures an emotion many seem to be feeling.</span></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">You might say it was a simple message that came from the heart.</p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong><span>RK: In previous newsletters I've spoken about how memes can lead to real impact—like we saw with</span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/09779cd7-d0c0-4a2e-a6bd-fdb1ffcbe549?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;"> NYPL here</a><span>. Beyond awareness, can you share how many clicks to</span></strong><span> </span><strong><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/5041df93-3e9b-4e4b-86b1-3ac9b8350776?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">Protect My Public Media</a><span> your efforts have led to?</span></strong></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong>CC: </strong><span>Your NYPL newsletter is a popular one on our team, and their experience did influence our strategy with the fist. Like any digital format, memes are not always the right choice for every message. But when they work, they work. And on top of stopping the scroll with an attention-grabber like the fist, we made sure to accompany the meme with what we felt was very necessary background info around the executive order and very direct calls-to-action in the post copy.</span></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">As I’m sure you understand firsthand, it is hard to track ROI and resulting actions. Some of our messaging contained direct links, some asked people to type the URL into a browser, and some sent users to our Linktree. What we do know is:</p><ul style="margin-top: 0;padding: 0;"><li style="margin: 8px 0 0 32px;mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style="color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: border-box;padding-left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;">Over three million people sent emails and phone calls to Congress supporting PBS through Protect My Public Media.</p></li><li style="margin: 8px 0 0 32px;mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style="color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: border-box;padding-left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;">Arthur’s Protect My Public Media campaign reached over 27 million impressions since our first post on May 2nd.</p></li><li style="margin: 8px 0 0 32px;mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style="color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: border-box;padding-left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;">In that first week of the campaign, the Arthur Linktree alone drove over 15,000 clicks to Protect My Public Media.</p></li></ul><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">This evidence is more than enough for us to know we had an impact. The majority of this credit goes to Arthur’s incredible community who were willing to take action to support public media.</p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong>RK: A few days ago congress devastatingly voted to roll back billions in public media funding. What does that mean for the Arthur social account?</strong></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong>CC: </strong><span>I honestly don’t know. We are still here as of now, and we are still posting. Everyone across public media is figuring out what exactly this all means and what the future looks like. We do know GBH is still committed to our mission, and Arthur is a huge part of that.</span></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong>RK: Finally,</strong><span> </span><strong><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/71c8c3f8-4b88-4a50-96f8-8bf4ebbdbb70?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">90% of parents believe PBS KIDS content</a><span> is a trusted and safe source for children. And PBS KIDS channels are </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/51e411e3-cb3e-45a6-8c27-d1c35be696d6?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">available to 98% of U.S. TV households</a><span>. I watched Arthur growing up and it was a formative program for me. What do we lose when access to public media is cut?</span></strong></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong>CC: </strong><span>Your information is absolutely right. PBS KIDS content is developed with early childhood experts that specialize in childhood development and is based in research and curriculum. About 50 percent of children in America don’t have access to pre-school and PBS KIDS programming is </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/921ec490-8536-485d-9d6c-acd01c45b312?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">proven to help close the achievement gap</a><span>. Marc Brown, the creator of Arthur, wrote an </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/8318fc43-a6e5-4f14-83dc-37ab78091ae2?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">excellent piece</a><span> about the impact PBS KIDS has.</span></p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">PBS is free and accessible to everyone, regardless of location or income. We’re also commercial-free and a non-profit—we are driven solely by our mission to inform and entertain the American public.</p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Many public media stations across the country rely on federal funding to distribute programming to their local areas. Without it, entire communities could lose access. In some remote areas of the country, this loss of information could even be dangerous.</p><p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54,55,55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>I recommend </span><a href="https://substack.com/redirect/5041df93-3e9b-4e4b-86b1-3ac9b8350776?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY" rel="" style="color: #6979d3;text-decoration: none;">ProtectMyPublicMedia.org</a><span> for more information.</span></p><div class="captioned-image-container-static" style="font-size: 16px;line-height: 26px;margin: 32px auto;"><figure View this post on the web at https://www.milkkarten.net/p/why-arthur-finally-posted-the-fist

In the early hours of July 18, congress voted [ https://substack.com/redirect/3eebc79f-293b-4221-9398-94f0f8a0092d?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] to strip $1.1 billion in already-approved funding for public media. It’s a devastating move that jeopardizes the essential services these stations provide to communities nationwide. 
During the lead up to these cuts an unlikely activist emerged: Arthur Read [ https://substack.com/redirect/cf71f4b2-03e8-4f48-bb86-94e71e72d822?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], the 8-year-old Aardvark main character of the book and television series Arthur. The official account for the PBS KIDS show has been using memes and clips to message and organize around the funding cuts. One post with the infamous fist meme [ https://substack.com/redirect/963d0f37-6a30-41c7-99fe-85fadec09ee6?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] garnered over 350K likes.
In today’s newsletter I am speaking with Cathleen Cusachs [ https://substack.com/redirect/5133803b-9382-4c5d-bc74-a12047f676ce?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], social media manager for GBH Kids [ https://substack.com/redirect/0cb12cd6-5916-4a6b-8108-c8bf56767afa?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] and person behind the @ArthurPBS [ https://substack.com/redirect/8d9e03e6-eafd-49e6-b3e6-3b79e02e3929?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] accounts. GBH is the largest producer of PBS programs in the country, and the home of popular PBS KIDS brands like Arthur, Molly of Denali, Pinkalicious & Peterrific, Work It Out Wombats!, and so many more.
We talk about leaning into lore, why they “wielded the power of the fist” for the first time ever, and how they drove over 15,000 clicks to Protect My Public Media [ https://substack.com/redirect/5041df93-3e9b-4e4b-86b1-3ac9b8350776?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ].
Sponsored by Slate [ https://substack.com/redirect/e042c916-6cff-4ab6-9562-90d42638f31a?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]
The content creation platform made for social teams
What do social accounts like Amazon, New York Knicks, and Vanity Fair have in common? They all use Slate [ https://substack.com/redirect/e042c916-6cff-4ab6-9562-90d42638f31a?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] to level up their content, enhance their real-time coverage, and speed up their workflows.
Here are a few of my favorite Slate features:
The Content Hub is a repository of all of your created content—organized and accessible at your (and your team’s) fingertips
Quickly auto-caption video content using your brand fonts and colors
Shortcuts uses AI to finds the best moments in your long-form video and creates ready to post edits for every social feed
Social safe zones to ensure your content fits overlays in TikTok, Reels, YouTube Shorts, and Stories

Rachel Karten: How would you describe the social strategy for Arthur?
Cathleen Cusachs: Arthur is unique compared to our other brands because it’s been active since 1996. So I’m not just talking to parents, guardians, and adults in current PBS kids’ lives, but also PBS kids who are now adults themselves. Our goal is to keep their relationship with Arthur healthy and positive.
Arthur’s longevity and success can be largely accredited to the show’s relatability, and we use that same framework for our social strategy. We hope to resonate with our Gen Z and Millennial audiences, recognizing their feelings and struggles, and do what we can to provide the emotional support Arthur is known for. And of course, bring some laughter and joy, too. It’s an added bonus if Arthur is top of mind when they eventually go to choose programming for their own children.
RK: I've read a bit about the content pillars the team set up for Arthur on TikTok—it’s a really clever framework. Can you share a bit more about those?
CC: The TikTok was first launched in 2022—before I joined GBH—as a team effort that consisted of the digital and marketing/communications teams at GBH and a Gen Z consulting firm. The launch’s goal was to lean into the fun of TikTok while also highlighting why Arthur is such an iconic brand in the children's media space. The content pillars created were:
“Girls That Get It Get It”: lean into the humor to remind audiences that Arthur is relatable and entertaining at any age.
“Not Me Crying Right Now”: celebrate iconic Arthur moments and the nostalgia.
“Read All About It”: Arthur was originally created to teach kids about reading but became a show about the joys of growing up so we choose clips that highlight the important lessons Arthur and his friends shared over the years.
As our account and audience have evolved, we don’t hold as strict to these original pillars, but they do still influence the base of our strategy. We want our accounts to exist as entertainment, an extension of Arthur content. This requires being mindful of how much promotion we do and never forgetting the core connections our audience has with the Elwood City squad. Foundational pillars have been a great way to do that.
RK: I love the idea of building content around how you want the audience to react. So smart. I think some children's shows and movies are reluctant to lean into their lore—it's been fun to see Shrek [ https://substack.com/redirect/cef287ab-023d-422d-ba54-afe351340cb5?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] finally embrace it, for example. How does Arthur lore and nostalgia play into your strategy?
CC: It’s at the core of it! Given our enormous catalog of show content, tapping into fan nostalgia and building community through our archives has been such a game-changer for us across so many GBH-affiliated accounts. A great example of how we utilize this is comment replies. Arthur fans often comment their favorite quotes, songs, or scenes on our posts, starting threads filled with nostalgia and wholesome memories. It’s incredibly heartwarming. We love to track down those clips and post them as comment replies [ https://substack.com/redirect/86af38ff-bd17-4c82-ab02-33525e6c9684?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], when we can. It encourages future engagement and introduces fan-favorite scenes to more viewers, but more importantly, it serves an audience that’s supported us since the beginning.
RK: Do you have an encyclopedic knowledge of clips and scenes from Arthur?
CC: I grew up watching Arthur myself and I am certainly more familiar than most, but unfortunately I do not have encyclopedic knowledge. 25 seasons is a lot to memorize! GBH has years of internal documentation I fall back on. I also collaborate closely with the Arthur producers, our communications/marketing team, and our digital team who all contribute their own expertise. There is also an incredibly detailed fan-run Arthur wiki [ https://substack.com/redirect/3c2ea6f9-ef11-47b2-a7bd-481c3880790b?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] that rivals our own in-house knowledge!
RK: I'd love to dig into how you've used the account to message and organize around the funding cuts. What did that strategy initially look like and how has it evolved over the past few months?
CC: This has been a group effort across the entire PBS landscape, rallying around Protect My Public Media [ https://substack.com/redirect/5041df93-3e9b-4e4b-86b1-3ac9b8350776?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]. For us, Arthur was a key part of this from the beginning. Like I emphasized earlier, we’ve spent years building trust and mutual support with our audience. We hoped this community agreed about the importance of PBS KIDS. Spoiler alert: They blew us away.
Our strategy was to use recognizable, familiar images and clips from the show with action-packed language to build awareness of the value of our programming and what’s at stake. As one of our posts said [ https://substack.com/redirect/766904c5-cfe2-45be-acdd-3309dbfd88d4?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], “We ride at dawn for PBS. Who’s riding with us?” That’s really like a thesis for our entire approach.
Our content matters and connects with people. We trusted in that legacy enough to tap into it. Conveying emotions of frustration, sadness and resiliency through beloved characters like Arthur, D.W., Sue Ellen, and others seems to really resonate with our fans.
RK: Can you talk about how the Arthur fist post [ https://substack.com/redirect/963d0f37-6a30-41c7-99fe-85fadec09ee6?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] came together?
CC: We call this internally The Day We Unleashed The Fist because it’s not a meme we use lightly. Arthur is a children’s show first and foremost, and we do have an obligation to keep our social accounts PG. So our relationship with the fist meme is a complicated one. If there was ever a time to use it, it was immediately following the executive order calling for the defunding of PBS.
If I’m going to ask people to listen to our arguments for why federal funding matters, I have to get them to care. The fist carries immediate recognition, strong emotional resonance, and a form of frankness that can be challenging to nail with a brand social channel. Having never previously wielded the power of the fist from the official Arthur POV also brought a certain level of seriousness. It was the perfect vessel for getting our message out quickly and effectively.
What surprised me was the lasting power of the meme! It’s not only still getting engagement, but I’ve come across reposts organically in comment sections, Reddit threads, and more. GBH has since made it into shirts [ https://substack.com/redirect/200f5a2e-9934-491c-a543-23c728f01632?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], stickers [ https://substack.com/redirect/a5d2d5f4-0f8c-441a-9e9b-472824941157?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], and even a gif [ https://substack.com/redirect/12e984ac-222c-4e10-a1ec-c544f63bf28a?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]. It was also featured on our 1,350 sq. ft. digital mural [ https://substack.com/redirect/2993d919-1be0-49ba-9f5c-9de365a86351?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] overlooking the Mass Pike. It clearly captures an emotion many seem to be feeling.
You might say it was a simple message that came from the heart.
RK: In previous newsletters I've spoken about how memes can lead to real impact—like we saw with NYPL here [ https://substack.com/redirect/09779cd7-d0c0-4a2e-a6bd-fdb1ffcbe549?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]. Beyond awareness, can you share how many clicks to Protect My Public Media [ https://substack.com/redirect/5041df93-3e9b-4e4b-86b1-3ac9b8350776?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] your efforts have led to?
CC: Your NYPL newsletter is a popular one on our team, and their experience did influence our strategy with the fist. Like any digital format, memes are not always the right choice for every message. But when they work, they work. And on top of stopping the scroll with an attention-grabber like the fist, we made sure to accompany the meme with what we felt was very necessary background info around the executive order and very direct calls-to-action in the post copy.
As I’m sure you understand firsthand, it is hard to track ROI and resulting actions. Some of our messaging contained direct links, some asked people to type the URL into a browser, and some sent users to our Linktree. What we do know is:
Over three million people sent emails and phone calls to Congress supporting PBS through Protect My Public Media.
Arthur’s Protect My Public Media campaign reached over 27 million impressions since our first post on May 2nd.
In that first week of the campaign, the Arthur Linktree alone drove over 15,000 clicks to Protect My Public Media.
This evidence is more than enough for us to know we had an impact. The majority of this credit goes to Arthur’s incredible community who were willing to take action to support public media.
RK: A few days ago congress devastatingly voted to roll back billions in public media funding. What does that mean for the Arthur social account?
CC: I honestly don’t know. We are still here as of now, and we are still posting. Everyone across public media is figuring out what exactly this all means and what the future looks like. We do know GBH is still committed to our mission, and Arthur is a huge part of that.
RK: Finally, 90% of parents believe PBS KIDS content [ https://substack.com/redirect/71c8c3f8-4b88-4a50-96f8-8bf4ebbdbb70?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] is a trusted and safe source for children. And PBS KIDS channels are available to 98% of U.S. TV households [ https://substack.com/redirect/51e411e3-cb3e-45a6-8c27-d1c35be696d6?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]. I watched Arthur growing up and it was a formative program for me. What do we lose when access to public media is cut?
CC: Your information is absolutely right. PBS KIDS content is developed with early childhood experts that specialize in childhood development and is based in research and curriculum. About 50 percent of children in America don’t have access to pre-school and PBS KIDS programming is proven to help close the achievement gap [ https://substack.com/redirect/921ec490-8536-485d-9d6c-acd01c45b312?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]. Marc Brown, the creator of Arthur, wrote an excellent piece [ https://substack.com/redirect/8318fc43-a6e5-4f14-83dc-37ab78091ae2?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] about the impact PBS KIDS has.
PBS is free and accessible to everyone, regardless of location or income. We’re also commercial-free and a non-profit—we are driven solely by our mission to inform and entertain the American public.
Many public media stations across the country rely on federal funding to distribute programming to their local areas. Without it, entire communities could lose access. In some remote areas of the country, this loss of information could even be dangerous.
I recommend ProtectMyPublicMedia.org [ https://substack.com/redirect/5041df93-3e9b-4e4b-86b1-3ac9b8350776?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] for more information.
Before I go, thank you to the over 800 subscribers who attended Link in Bio’s private call with Instagram. There’s no recording of the meeting, but this recap is really great [ https://substack.com/redirect/556132e8-77fb-4e5a-b4b0-61f570b3bb2f?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]. Instagram also gave the Link in Bio community an exclusive look at a new feature [ https://substack.com/redirect/aecd79c3-6f43-4c54-9d73-6c48ec4bb35f?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] coming to Insights—you'll be able to see at what part of a reel or on what slide of a carousel someone pressed like. Is there a topic you want the Instagram team to dive into at the next meeting?
Finally, if you enjoy free interviews like this one, you can upgrade to a paid Link in Bio subscription [ https://substack.com/redirect/d98f554e-8fbd-44da-aca8-9d9d61056077?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]. You’ll get access to the very active and very entertaining Discord.
It’s likely an educational expense at your company—here’s a template [ https://substack.com/redirect/d0fba3a7-6329-445e-9a23-ad532b3f09db?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] for you to use when asking your manager.

Unsubscribe https://substack.com/redirect/2/eyJlIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubWlsa2thcnRlbi5uZXQvYWN0aW9uL2Rpc2FibGVfZW1haWw_.tsRapJX-IVSSLwBjYY8DV9ta2PlIKpz0WJnyU1XbhlA?

In the early hours of July 18, congress voted [ https://substack.com/redirect/3eebc79f-293b-4221-9398-94f0f8a0092d?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] to strip $1.1 billion in already-approved funding for public media. It’s a devastating move that jeopardizes the essential services these stations provide to communities nationwide.
During the lead up to these cuts an unlikely activist emerged: Arthur Read [ https://substack.com/redirect/cf71f4b2-03e8-4f48-bb86-94e71e72d822?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], the 8-year-old Aardvark main character of the book and television series Arthur. The official account for the PBS KIDS show has been using memes and clips to message and organize around the funding cuts. One post with the infamous fist meme [ https://substack.com/redirect/963d0f37-6a30-41c7-99fe-85fadec09ee6?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] garnered over 350K likes.
In today’s newsletter I am speaking with Cathleen Cusachs [ https://substack.com/redirect/5133803b-9382-4c5d-bc74-a12047f676ce?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ], social media manager for GBH Kids [ https://substack.com/redirect/0cb12cd6-5916-4a6b-8108-c8bf56767afa?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] and person behind the @ArthurPBS [ https://substack.com/redirect/8d9e03e6-eafd-49e6-b3e6-3b79e02e3929?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] accounts. GBH is the largest producer of PBS programs in the country, and the home of popular PBS KIDS brands like Arthur, Molly of Denali, Pinkalicious & Peterrific, Work It Out Wombats!, and so many more.
We talk about leaning into lore, why they “wielded the power of the fist” for the first time ever, and how they drove over 15,000 clicks to Protect My Public Media [ https://substack.com/redirect/5041df93-3e9b-4e4b-86b1-3ac9b8350776?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ].
Sponsored by Slate [ https://substack.com/redirect/e042c916-6cff-4ab6-9562-90d42638f31a?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ]
The content creation platform made for social teams
What do social accounts like Amazon, New York Knicks, and Vanity Fair have in common? They all use Slate [ https://substack.com/redirect/e042c916-6cff-4ab6-9562-90d42638f31a?j=eyJ1IjoiNGMxZ2E4In0.Yzm-Xy6ZeHeheoYxDFW0oeKyEk1wC18tVT9Gj26j3SY ] to level up their content, enhance their real-time coverage, and speed up their workflows.
Here are a few of my favorite Slate features:
The Content Hub is a repository of all of your created content—organized and accessible at your (and your team’s) fingertips
Quickly auto-caption video content using your brand fonts and colors
Shortcuts uses AI to finds the best moments in your long-form video and creates ready to post edits for every social feed
Social safe zones to ensure your content fits overlays in TikTok, Reels, YouTube Shorts, and Stories
Slate is perfect for social teams that are tired of texting “finalfinalfinal.mp4” for approval and are drowning in a sea of screenshots. One place to create for every social channel. Built for social managers, by social managers.
